This paper is likely to belong to the cs.DB (Databases) sub-category as it deals with indexing moving objects and improving query performance of indexes. It may also belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as it proposes a novel speed partitioning technique based on dynamic programming. Additionally, it may be relevant to cs.IR (Information Retrieval) as it discusses improving search space expansion and query performance. It could also be relevant to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it deals with analyzing patterns of moving objects. Finally, it may be relevant to cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science) as it proposes a computational solution to the optimal speed partitioning problem.
